08142716/http://www.acronym.org.uk/dd/dd77/77mda.htm Negotiations for extension to treaty] (2004)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080118030158/http://www.awe.co.uk/main_site/about_awe/history/timeline/1958/ US-UK Agreement], [[Atomic Weapons Establishment]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041217064919/http://www.basicint.org/nuclear/MDAlegal.htm Mutual Defence Agreement and the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty \u2013 Legal Opinion]\n\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Portal bar|Politics|United Kingdom|Nuclear technology}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1958 US-UK Mutual Defence Agreement}}\n[[Category:1958 in military history]]\n[[Category:1958 in the United Kingdom|Mutual Defence Agreement]]\n[[Category:1958 in the United States|Mutual Defence Agreement]]\n[[Category:Cold War treaties]]\n[[Category:Nuclear history of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Nuclear weapons program of the United States]]\n[[Category:Treaties concluded in 1958]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom\u2013United States treaties]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom\u2013United States military relations]]\n", "name_user": "My account for March 31, 2020", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1958_US%E2%80%93UK_Mutual_Defence_Agreement"}
{"title_page": "Slatina, Romania", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Olt\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_map              = Slatina jud Olt.png\n|map_caption            = Location in Olt County\n|official_name=Slatina\n|image_skyline = RO OT Slatina center from Gradiste hill 1.jpg\n|image_shield=Coa_Slatina_RO.gif\n|coordinates = {{coord|44|25|47|N|24|21|51|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|leader_party = PSD\n|leader_name=Constantin Stelian Emil Mo\u0163\n|area_total_km2=53.93\n|website={{url|http://www.primariaslatina.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''Slatina''' ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8slatina}}, {{lang-bg|\u0421\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430}}) is the capital city of [[Olt County]], [[Romania]], on the [[Olt River|river Olt]]. It is located in the south of Romania, on the eastern side of the river Olt, in the historical region of [[Muntenia]]. The population was 70,293 in 2011, being an important industrial center.\n\nThe city administers one village, Cirea\u0219ov.\n\n==History==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1912 |9825\n|1930 |11243\n|1948 |13136\n|1956 |13381\n|1966 |19250\n|1977 |44892\n|1992 |85168\n|2002 |79171\n|2011 |70293\n}}\n\nThe town of Slatina was first mentioned on January 20, 1368 in an official document issued by [[Vladislav I of Wallachia|Vladislav I Vlaicu]], [[List of rulers of Wallachia|Prince]] of [[Wallachia]]. The document stated that merchants from the [[Transylvania]]n city of [[Bra\u0219ov]] would not pay [[customs]] when passing through Slatina. The word ''Slatina'' is of [[Slavic languages|Slavic]] origin, and means \"''marsh, swamp, watery plain''\".<ref>Carl Voretzsch, Romanistische Arbeiten, Volume 54, Issue 2, M. Niemeyer, 1960, p. 504.</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n[[Alro Slatina]], the largest [[aluminum]] producing factories in [[Southeastern Europe]], is located in the city. Other companies based in Slatina include ALPROM (which, like ALRO, is a [[subsidiary]] of VIMETCOGROUP), [[Altur]] (engine set manufacturer), [[Pirelli]] Tires Romania (tire-manufacturer), Steel Cord Romania (steel cord for tires), TMK Artrom (seamless steel tubes), Prysmian (electronic and electric wires and cables) and Benteler.\n\nOne of the oldest private businesses in Romania is the Slatina-based pastry shop ''Atletul Albanez'' (\"The [[Albania]]n Athlete\").<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.gandul.info/articol_8352/atletul_albanez_al_halvitei_cu_braga.html \"Atletul albanez al halvi\u021bei cu brag\u0103\" (\"The Albanian Athlete of Nougat and Boza\")]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, in ''[[G\u00e2ndul]]'', April 12, 2006</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[Image:\"1 Mai\" Stadion.jpg|thumb|right|300px]] -->\nThere is an [[Football (soccer)|association football]] club in Slatina, [[CSM Slatina (football)|CSM Slatina]], that plays in [[Liga III]] (the third league of Romania).\n\nThe women's handball section of CSM Slatina also represent the city in the top handball league of Romania.\n\n==Natives==\n* [[Petre S. Aurelian]] - politician\n* [[Aurelia Br\u0103deanu]] - handball player\n* [[Ionel D\u0103nciulescu]] - football player\n* [[Felicia Filip]] - operatic soprano\n* [[Iulian Filipescu]] - football player\n* [[M\u0103d\u0103lina Diana Ghenea]] - actress and model\n* [[Eug\u00e8ne Ionesco]] - playwright\n* [[Claudiu Niculescu]] - football player\n* [[Monica Niculescu]] - tennis player\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Slatina, Romania}}\n* [http://gigi.feraru.eu/2012/04/livecam-slatina-olt.html Livecam Slatina, Olt --- Strada Cri\u0219an (Libert\u0103\u021bii - Prim\u0103verii)]\n\n{{Olt County}}\n{{RoJudCapitals}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Capitals of Romanian counties]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Olt County]]\n[[Category:Place names of Slavic origin in Romania]]\n[[Category:Slatina, Romania| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = municipality\n|county                 = Olt\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Olt County\n|official_name=Slatina\n|image_skyline = RO OT Slatina center from Gradiste hill 1.jpg\n|image_shield=Coa_Slatina_RO.gif\n|coordinates = {{coord|44|25|47|N|24|21|51|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|leader_party = [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|PSD]]\n|leader_name=Constantin Stelian Emil Mo\u0163\n|area_total_km2=53.93\n|website={{url|http://www.primariaslatina.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''Slatina''' ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8slatina}}, {{lang-bg|\u0421\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430}}) is the capital city of [[Olt County]], [[Romania]], on the [[Olt River|river Olt]]. It is located in the south of Romania, on the eastern side of the river Olt, in the historical region of [[Muntenia]]. The population was 70,293 in 2011, being an important industrial center.\n\nThe city administers one village, Cirea\u0219ov.\n\n==History==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1912 |9825\n|1930 |11243\n|1948 |13136\n|1956 |13381\n|1966 |19250\n|1977 |44892\n|1992 |85168\n|2002 |79171\n|2011 |70293\n}}\n\nThe town of Slatina was first mentioned on January 20, 1368 in an official document issued by [[Vladislav I of Wallachia|Vladislav I Vlaicu]], [[List of rulers of Wallachia|Prince]] of [[Wallachia]]. The document stated that merchants from the [[Transylvania]]n city of [[Bra\u0219ov]] would not pay [[customs]] when passing through Slatina. The word ''Slatina'' is of [[Slavic languages|Slavic]] origin, and means \"''marsh, swamp, watery plain''\".<ref>Carl Voretzsch, Romanistische Arbeiten, Volume 54, Issue 2, M. Niemeyer, 1960, p. 504.</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n[[Alro Slatina]], the largest [[aluminum]] producing factories in [[Southeastern Europe]], is located in the city. Other companies based in Slatina include ALPROM (which, like ALRO, is a [[subsidiary]] of VIMETCOGROUP), [[Altur]] (engine set manufacturer), [[Pirelli]] Tires Romania (tire-manufacturer), Steel Cord Romania (steel cord for tires), TMK Artrom (seamless steel tubes), Prysmian (electronic and electric wires and cables) and Benteler.\n\nOne of the oldest private businesses in Romania is the Slatina-based pastry shop ''Atletul Albanez'' (\"The [[Albania]]n Athlete\").<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.gandul.info/articol_8352/atletul_albanez_al_halvitei_cu_braga.html \"Atletul albanez al halvi\u021bei cu brag\u0103\" (\"The Albanian Athlete of Nougat and Boza\")]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, in ''[[G\u00e2ndul]]'', April 12, 2006</ref>\n\n==Sport==\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[Image:\"1 Mai\" Stadion.jpg|thumb|right|300px]] -->\nThere is an [[Football (soccer)|association football]] club in Slatina, [[CSM Slatina (football)|CSM Slatina]], that plays in [[Liga III]] (the third league of Romania).\n\nThe women's handball section of CSM Slatina also represent the city in the top handball league of Romania.\n\n==Natives==\n* [[Petre S. Aurelian]] - politician\n* [[Aurelia Br\u0103deanu]] - handball player\n* [[Ionel D\u0103nciulescu]] - football player\n* [[Felicia Filip]] - operatic soprano\n* [[Iulian Filipescu]] - football player\n* [[M\u0103d\u0103lina Diana Ghenea]] - actress and model\n* [[Eug\u00e8ne Ionesco]] - playwright\n* [[Claudiu Niculescu]] - football player\n* [[Monica Niculescu]] - tennis player\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Slatina, Romania}}\n* [http://gigi.feraru.eu/2012/04/livecam-slatina-olt.html Livecam Slatina, Olt --- Strada Cri\u0219an (Libert\u0103\u021bii - Prim\u0103verii)]\n\n{{Olt County}}\n{{RoJudCapitals}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Romania]]\n[[Category:Capitals of Romanian counties]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Olt County]]\n[[Category:Place names of Slavic origin in Romania]]\n[[Category:Slatina, Romania| ]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slatina,_Romania"}
{"title_page": "Kwame Awuah-Darko", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kwame Awuah-Darko\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Kingsley Kwame Awuah-Darko\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1969|01|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[Accra]], [[Ghana]]\n| status             = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology]] (Hons) (LLB) <br> [[Henley Business School]] (Mba)\n| occupation         = [[Politician]]\n| years_active       = \n| employer           = \n| known for          = Founder of Matrix Holdings International <br>Founder of Roman Ridge School\n| party              = [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana) | National Democratic Congress]]\n| spouse             = {{Marriage|Nana Yaa Oteng|1986}}\n| partner            = \n| children           = {{flatlist|\n* Nana Kojo Awuah-darko\n* Obrempong Kojo Awuah-Darko\n* Okatakyie Kwesi Awuah-Darko\n}}\n| parents            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Nana Awuah Darko Ampem I]] \n* Judith Ellen Achempong\n}}\n| website            = {{url|www.kwame.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Kwame Awuah-Darko''' (born January 4th, 1969) is a Ghanaian politician and banker. He is the son of [[Nana Awuah Darko Ampem I|Nana Awuah-Darko Ampem I]], the [[Nana Awuah Darko Ampem I#Chieftaincy|Nkosuohene of Asante Juaben traditional area]] in the Ashanti Region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsghana.com.gh/the-80-wealthiest-people-in-ghana/|title=The 80 wealthiest people in Ghana|last=Ghana|first=News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nKwame Awuah-Darko was born in Accra. He is a native of the [[Ashanti Empire|Ashanti kingdom]] and the [[Akyem Abuakwa|Akyem Abuakwa State]]. Awuah-Darko is the third son of [[Nana Awuah Darko Ampem I|Nana Awuah-Darko Ampem I]], the [[Nana Awuah Darko Ampem I#Chieftaincy|Nkosuohene of Asante Juaben traditional area]] in the Ashanti Region. He attended [[St. Peter's Mission Schools|St. Peters School]] and [[Achimota School]]. He holds B.A. Law (Hons) from the [[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology]], [[Kumasi]] and an MBA from the [[Henley Business School]], Greenlands, [[United Kingdom]].\n\n== Career ==\nHe is the founder of Matrix Holdings International and Money Systems International, and the co-founder of Roman Ridge School.  He served as Board Member of State Insurance Company (SIC) Limited<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.com.gh/news/kwame-awuah-darko-former-bost-md-sues-ken-agyapong-for-ghc5m/z5yk2xs|title=Former BOST MD sues Ken Agyapong for GHC5m|date=2017-07-05|website=Pulse Gh|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> as well as Board Chairman of the SIC Financial Services Limited respectively from 2009 to 2012. In addition, Kwame served as Director and Board Member of City Investment Company Limited. He contributed to the establishment Commercial Bank, a financial institution in Ghana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/I-can-t-steal-money-through-Chief-of-Staff-Account-Awuah-Darko-685928|title=I can\u2019t steal money through Chief of Staff Account \u2013 Awuah-Darko|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Court-chases-Awuah-Darko-572336|title=Court chases Awuah-Darko|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Awuah-Darko currently serves on the board of the Roman Ridge School which he co-founded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peacefmonline.com/pages/local/news/201603/274058.php|title=Kwame Awuah Darko -The Exceptional Ghanaian|last=Online|first=Peace FM|website=www.peacefmonline.com|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\nIn 2012, Kwame was elected to run for parliament as the candidate representing the [[Ayawaso West]] Wuogon Constituency under the [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress (NDC)]].\n\nIn October 2013, he was appointed by the [[Government of Ghana]] to serve as the Managing Director of Ghana\u2019s largest Petroleum Storage and Logistics Company, Bulk Oil Storage and Transportation Company Limited (BOST).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/business/Awuah-Darko-holds-two-MD-positions-at-BOST-TOR-374957|title=Awuah-Darko holds two MD positions at BOST, TOR|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> He established a petroleum-trading department within the company, trading mainly petroleum products such as [[Gasoline]], [[Fuel oil|Gasoil]], [[Liquefied petroleum gas|LPG]] and [[Petroleum|Crude Oil]]. \n\nThe government of Ghana in June 2015, appointed Kwame Awuah as the Chief Executive Officer of Ghana\u2019s National Petroleum Refinery Asset, the Tema Oil Refinery (TOR).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.com.gh/ece-frontpage/tema-oil-refinery-tor-to-increase-daily-crude-production-by-20000-barrels/vnhmltp|title=TOR to increase daily crude production by 20,000 barrels|date=2016-12-19|website=Pulse Gh|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn line with [[John Mahama|John Dramani Mahama\u2019s]] vision of making Ghana the Petroleum Hub of West Africa, he successfully implemented and oversaw the trade of petroleum products which exported gasoline and gasoil to neighboring countries such as, [[Mali]], [[Niger]], [[Burkina Faso]], [[Ivory Coast]], [[Benin]], [[Nigeria]] and [[Liberia]] among other countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.reportingoilandgas.org/bost-to-fuel-burkinabe-market-mali-and-others-follow-later/|title=BOST to fuel Burkinabe market \u2026Mali and others follow later {{!}} Comprehensive Ghana Oil and Gas news, information, updates, analysis|website=www.reportingoilandgas.org|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\n== Personal life ==\nKwame Awuah-Darko is married to Nana Yaa Oteng with two sons. He is a cousin to [[Paul Boateng|Lord Paul Boateng]] of Akyem and [[Wembley|Wembley,]] the late [[J. B. Danquah-Adu|J.B Danquah Adu]] and Frank Adu Jnr, former Managing Director of Cal Bank. He is also brother to Daniel Awuah-Darko, Harold Awuah-Darko and David Awuah-Darko.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Awuah-Darko, Kwame}}\n[[Category:University of Ghana alumni]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Congress (Ghana) politicians]]\n[[Category:Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Eastern Region (Ghana)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kwame Awuah-Darko\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Kingsley Kwame Awuah-Darko\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1969|01|04}}\n| birth_place        = [[Accra]], [[Ghana]]\n| status             = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology]] (Hons) (LLB) <br> [[Henley Business School]] (Mba)\n| occupation         = [[Politician]]\n| years_active       = \n| employer           = \n| known for          = Founder of Matrix Holdings International <br>Founder of Roman Ridge School\n| party              = [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana) | National Democratic Congress]]\n| spouse             = {{Marriage|Nana Yaa Oteng|1986}}\n| partner            = \n| children           = {{flatlist|\n* Nana Kojo Awuah-darko\n* Obrempong Kojo Awuah-Darko\n* Okatakyie Kwesi Awuah-Darko\n}}\n| parents            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Nana Awuah Darko Ampem I]] \n* Judith Ellen Achempong\n}}\n| website            = {{url|www.kwame.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Kwame Awuah-Darko''' (born January 4th, 1969) is a Ghanaian business magnate, politician and banker. He is the son of [[Nana Awuah Darko Ampem I|Nana Awuah-Darko Ampem I]], the [[Nana Awuah Darko Ampem I#Chieftaincy|Nkosuohene of Asante Juaben traditional area]] in the Ashanti Region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newsghana.com.gh/the-80-wealthiest-people-in-ghana/|title=The 80 wealthiest people in Ghana|last=Ghana|first=News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nKwame Awuah-Darko was born in Accra. He is a native of the [[Ashanti Empire|Ashanti kingdom]] and the [[Akyem Abuakwa|Akyem Abuakwa State]]. Awuah-Darko is the third son of [[Nana Awuah Darko Ampem I|Nana Awuah-Darko Ampem I]], the [[Nana Awuah Darko Ampem I#Chieftaincy|Nkosuohene of Asante Juaben traditional area]] in the Ashanti Region. He attended [[St. Peter's Mission Schools|St. Peters School]] and [[Achimota School]]. He holds B.A. Law (Hons) from the [[Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology]], [[Kumasi]] and an MBA from the [[Henley Business School]], Greenlands, [[United Kingdom]].\n\n== Career ==\nHe is the founder of Matrix Holdings International and Money Systems International, and the co-founder of Roman Ridge School.  He served as Board Member of State Insurance Company (SIC) Limited<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.com.gh/news/kwame-awuah-darko-former-bost-md-sues-ken-agyapong-for-ghc5m/z5yk2xs|title=Former BOST MD sues Ken Agyapong for GHC5m|date=2017-07-05|website=Pulse Gh|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> as well as Board Chairman of the SIC Financial Services Limited respectively from 2009 to 2012. In addition, Kwame served as Director and Board Member of City Investment Company Limited. He contributed to the establishment Commercial Bank, a financial institution in Ghana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/I-can-t-steal-money-through-Chief-of-Staff-Account-Awuah-Darko-685928|title=I can\u2019t steal money through Chief of Staff Account \u2013 Awuah-Darko|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Court-chases-Awuah-Darko-572336|title=Court chases Awuah-Darko|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> Awuah-Darko currently serves on the board of the Roman Ridge School which he co-founded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peacefmonline.com/pages/local/news/201603/274058.php|title=Kwame Awuah Darko -The Exceptional Ghanaian|last=Online|first=Peace FM|website=www.peacefmonline.com|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\nIn 2012, Kwame was elected to run for parliament as the candidate representing the [[Ayawaso West]] Wuogon Constituency under the [[National Democratic Congress (Ghana)|National Democratic Congress (NDC)]].\n\nIn October 2013, he was appointed by the [[Government of Ghana]] to serve as the Managing Director of Ghana\u2019s largest Petroleum Storage and Logistics Company, Bulk Oil Storage and Transportation Company Limited (BOST).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/business/Awuah-Darko-holds-two-MD-positions-at-BOST-TOR-374957|title=Awuah-Darko holds two MD positions at BOST, TOR|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> He established a petroleum-trading department within the company, trading mainly petroleum products such as [[Gasoline]], [[Fuel oil|Gasoil]], [[Liquefied petroleum gas|LPG]] and [[Petroleum|Crude Oil]]. \n\nThe government of Ghana in June 2015, appointed Kwame Awuah as the Chief Executive Officer of Ghana\u2019s National Petroleum Refinery Asset, the Tema Oil Refinery (TOR).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.com.gh/ece-frontpage/tema-oil-refinery-tor-to-increase-daily-crude-production-by-20000-barrels/vnhmltp|title=TOR to increase daily crude production by 20,000 barrels|date=2016-12-19|website=Pulse Gh|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nIn line with [[John Mahama|John Dramani Mahama\u2019s]] vision of making Ghana the Petroleum Hub of West Africa, he successfully implemented and oversaw the trade of petroleum products which exported gasoline and gasoil to neighboring countries such as, [[Mali]], [[Niger]], [[Burkina Faso]], [[Ivory Coast]], [[Benin]], [[Nigeria]] and [[Liberia]] among other countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.reportingoilandgas.org/bost-to-fuel-burkinabe-market-mali-and-others-follow-later/|title=BOST to fuel Burkinabe market \u2026Mali and others follow later {{!}} Comprehensive Ghana Oil and Gas news, information, updates, analysis|website=www.reportingoilandgas.org|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\n== Personal life ==\nKwame Awuah-Darko is married to Nana Yaa Oteng with two sons. He is a cousin to [[Paul Boateng|Lord Paul Boateng]] of Akyem and [[Wembley|Wembley,]] the late [[J. B. Danquah-Adu|J.B Danquah Adu]] and Frank Adu Jnr, former Managing Director of Cal Bank. He is also brother to Daniel Awuah-Darko, Harold Awuah-Darko and David Awuah-Darko.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Awuah-Darko, Kwame}}\n[[Category:University of Ghana alumni]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:National Democratic Congress (Ghana) politicians]]\n[[Category:Kwame Nkrumah University of Science and Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Eastern Region (Ghana)]]\n", "name_user": "Kwamevaughan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kwame_Awuah-Darko"}
{"title_page": "Randy Lee Cutler", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour = #6495ED\n| name = Randy Lee Cutler\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Quebec, Canada]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Canadian]]\n| field = Writer, Artist, Educator\n| training = \n| movement = \n| works = \n| patrons = \n| influenced by = \n| influenced = \n| awards = Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council Insight Grant, Ian Gillespie Design and Dynamic Media Grant, Ian Wallace Teaching Award, ECU 2011\n| elected = \n| website = http://randyleecutler.com\n}}\n'''Randy Lee Cutler''' is a writer, academic, educator and artist working in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].  She has a [[PhD]] in [[Cultural History]] from the [[Royal College of Art]].  Her work and writing aim to understand knowledge, how it circulates, and how it leads to interpretation.  She currently works as a [[Associate Professor|Professor]] at [[Emily Carr University of Art and Design]] in the Faculty of Art.\n\n==Writing==\nHer contribution:''Vancouver Singular Plural: Art in an Age of Post-Medium Practice'' to the seminal Vancouver Anthology; ''Vancouver Art & Economies'' edited by Melanie O'Brian and published by [[Arsenal Pulp Press]] and [[Artspeak]] was reviewed as critiquing the terms of new media by offering an alternative vantage point on artists who embrace plurality, rather than medium specificity, through 'post-medium practices.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hutchinson|first1=Kristen|title=Vancouver Art & Economies (review)|journal=University of Toronto Quarterly|date=Winter 2010|volume=79|issue=1|pages= 457\u2013458|doi=10.1353/utq.2010.0211}}</ref>\n\nHer Essay ''O My friends\u2026: On Friendship and Artistic Practice'' was commissioned by artists [[Marina Roy]] and [[Abbas Akhavan]] for a catalogue on their work published by Malaspina Printmakers Society, Vancouver, BC in 2014.  In the essay, Cutler explains; \"Beyond its primary role in our emotional lives, there is a particular kind of friendship, a type of intimate relation that resides in what can be described as artistic friendship, edifying and feeding creative endeavors.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Muir|first1=Justin|title=fire/fire: marina roy & abbas akhavan|date=2012|publisher=Malaspina Gallery & Centre A|location=Vancouver|url=http://www.malaspinaprintmakers.com/fire-fire%3A-marina-roy-and-abbas-akhavan/dp/4748}}</ref> The essay uses theories of friendship through history, philosophers and cultural thinkers, and evolves its understanding towards its relationship to sensory connections within artistic acts.\n\n===Select Publications and Writing===\n*''Crystal Queer'' <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cutler|first1=Randy Lee|title=Crystal Queer|journal=Contemporary Verse 2: The Canadian Journal of Poetry and Critical Writing|date=2015}}</ref> The Canadian Journal of Poetry and Critical Writing, 2015\n*''On Speculative Walking:  From the Peripatetic to the Peristaltic'' <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cutler|first1=Randy Lee|title=On Speculative Walking|journal=C Magazine|date=2014}}</ref> C Magazine, 2014\n*''Review:  Il Palazzo Enciclopedico:  The 55th International Art Exhibition'' <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cutler|first1=Randy Lee|title=Il Palazzo Encicilopedico|journal=C Magazine|date=Fall 2013}}</ref> C Magazine, Fall 2013\n*''FeminismS without End...'' <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cutler|first1=Randy Lee|title=FeminismS without End...|journal=Texte zur Kunst FUSE Magazine|date=2012}}</ref> FUSE Magazine, Fall 2012\n*''Making Metaphors''<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cutler|first1=Randy Lee|title=Making Metaphors|journal=Visual Arts Research|date=2010|volume=40|issue=1}}</ref>*''A Spectrum of Difference'' <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cutler|first1=Randy Lee|title=A Spectrum of Difference|journal=Fillip|date=Spring 2009|volume=9}}</ref> Fillip Review, Spring 2009\n\n==Art practice==\nRandy Lee Cutler works in various media from collage to performance, textual practices, digital e-books and posters. Her alias, Hedda Cabbage made an appearance at Fuse at the [[Vancouver Art Gallery]] co-presented by Live Biennale.\n\n===Saltwalks===\n\n''Saltwalks:Three Movements'' in conjunction with Access Gallery, was a work that consisted of performative \"interactions with the public initiated through taste tests of different kinds of edible salt\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Visualeyez|first1=Randy Lee Cutler|url=http://www.visualeyez.org/festival-2010/artists/randy-lee-cutler/|title=Ask me about salt}}</ref> As a work of social practice,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tse|first1=Naomi|title=Salt walks represent new form of social practice art|journal=The Source Forum of Diversity|date=May 27, 2014|volume=14|issue=9|url=http://thelasource.com/en/2014/05/26/salt-walks-represent-new-form-of-social-practice-art/}}</ref> the walks began with a salt tasting and led into an understanding salt's influence in social and cultural development.  The three walks were each navigated within a theme.  The first theme of herbal medicine featured Chinese herbal remedies with herbalist Albert Fok  The second on food preservation exposed participants to the influence salt and salt extraction had on food, the geography, and harvests and featured local artist Howie Tsui.  The final walk focused on the crystal structures of salt towards a vibrational healing energy power and featured a visit with local Chinatown crystal shop owner, Edward Gutierrez.\n\n===Open Wide===\n\nIn 2014 she released ''Open Wide: An Abecedarium for the Great Digestive System'', an [[ebook]] on digestion as a metaphor for experience.  The book mimics the digestive system, and its chronology is run by the alphabet.  It features illustrations, media and sound by [[Abbas Akhavan]], Myron Campbell, Gaye Chan, John Cussans, [[Geoffrey Farmer]], Kristina Fiedrich, Monique Fouquet, [[Allison Hrabluik]], Elvira Hufschmid, Ingrid Koenig, [[Germaine Koh]], [[Elizabeth MacKenzie]], [[Liz Magor]], Graham Meisner, Cindy Mochizuki, Damian Moppett, Ranu Mukherjee, Ryan Peter, [[Marina Roy]], Margit Schild, and [[Holly Schmidt]].\n\n===Select exhibitions/screenings===\n*''Salt Walks,'' for part of the group show Gleaners, Nanaimo Art Gallery, BC 2015\n*''A Joyful Wisdom'' collages and vitrine installation, part of the group show Beside Yourself, AHVA Gallery, Audain Art Centre, University of British Columbia, 2014\n*''Salt Walks: Three Movements,'' at VIVO Media Arts Centre, Vancouver, BC, 2014\n*''By Way of the Intersection,'' part of the Shelved curatorial project with Burnaby Art Gallery and Artspeak Gallery, Vancouver, BC, 2014\n*''Salt Walks: Three Movements,'' at Dr. Sun Yat-Sen Classical Chinese Garden in collaboration with Access Gallery, Vancouver, BC, 2014\n*''Kitchen Semiotics,'' Innovate Heritage: Conversations between Arts and Heritage, an international trans-disciplinary conference, Berlin, Germany, 2014\n\n==Interviews==\n*Jeremy Todd: A Conversation w/Randy Lee Cutler<ref>{{cite web|last1=VIVO Media Arts Centre|first1=Jeremy Todd|url=http://www.vivomediaarts.com/a-conversation-w-randy-lee-cutler/|title=A Conversation w/ Randy Lee Cutler}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cutler, Randy Lee}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:LGBT artists from Canada]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Art]]\n[[Category:Emily Carr University of Art and Design faculty]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Canada]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour = #6495ED\n| name = Randy Lee Cutler\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Quebec, Canada]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Canadian]]\n| field = Writer, Artist, Educator\n| training = \n| movement = \n| works = \n| patrons = \n| influenced by = \n| influenced = \n| awards = Social Sciences and Humanities Research Council Insight Grant, Ian Gillespie Design and Dynamic Media Grant,Ian Wallace Teaching Award, ECU 2011\n| elected = \n| website = http://randyleecutler.com\n}}\n'''Randy Lee Cutler''' is a writer, academic, educator and artist working in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].  She has a [[PhD]] in [[Cultural History]] from the [[Royal College of Art]].  Her work and writing aim to understand knowledge, how it circulates, and how it leads to interpretation.  She currently works as a [[Associate Professor|Professor]] at [[Emily Carr University of Art and Design]] in the Faculty of Art.\n\n==Writing==\nHer contribution:''Vancouver Singular Plural: Art in an Age of Post-Medium Practice'' to the seminal Vancouver Anthology; ''Vancouver Art & Economies'' edited by Melanie O'Brian and published by [[Arsenal Pulp Press]] and [[Artspeak]] was reviewed as critiquing the terms of new media by offering an alternative vantage point on artists who embrace plurality, rather than medium specificity, through 'post-medium practices.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hutchinson|first1=Kristen|title=Vancouver Art & Economies (review)|journal=University of Toronto Quarterly|date=Winter 2010|volume=79|issue=1|pages= 457\u2013458|doi=10.1353/utq.2010.0211}}</ref>\n\nHer Essay ''O My friends\u2026: On Friendship and Artistic Practice'' was commissioned by artists [[Marina Roy]] and [[Abbas Akhavan]] for a catalogue on their work published by Malaspina Printmakers Society, Vancouver, BC in 2014.  In the essay, Cutler explains; \"Beyond its primary role in our emotional lives, there is a particular kind of friendship, a type of intimate relation that resides in what can be described as artistic friendship, edifying and feeding creative endeavors.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Muir|first1=Justin|title=fire/fire: marina roy & abbas akhavan|date=2012|publisher=Malaspina Gallery & Centre A|location=Vancouver|url=http://www.malaspinaprintmakers.com/fire-fire%3A-marina-roy-and-abbas-akhavan/dp/4748}}</ref> The essay uses theories of friendship through history, philosophers and cultural thinkers, and evolves its understanding towards its relationship to sensory connections within artistic acts.\n\n===Select Publications and Writing===\n*''Crystal Queer'' <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cutler|first1=Randy Lee|title=Crystal Queer|journal=Contemporary Verse 2: The Canadian Journal of Poetry and Critical Writing|date=2015}}</ref> The Canadian Journal of Poetry and Critical Writing, 2015\n*''On Speculative Walking:  From the Peripatetic to the Peristaltic'' <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cutler|first1=Randy Lee|title=On Speculative Walking|journal=C Magazine|date=2014}}</ref> C Magazine, 2014\n*''Review:  Il Palazzo Enciclopedico:  The 55th International Art Exhibition'' <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cutler|first1=Randy Lee|title=Il Palazzo Encicilopedico|journal=C Magazine|date=Fall 2013}}</ref> C Magazine, Fall 2013\n*''FeminismS without End...'' <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cutler|first1=Randy Lee|title=FeminismS without End...|journal=Texte zur Kunst FUSE Magazine|date=2012}}</ref> FUSE Magazine, Fall 2012\n*''Making Metaphors''<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cutler|first1=Randy Lee|title=Making Metaphors|journal=Visual Arts Research|date=2010|volume=40|issue=1}}</ref>*''A Spectrum of Difference'' <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cutler|first1=Randy Lee|title=A Spectrum of Difference|journal=Fillip|date=Spring 2009|volume=9}}</ref> Fillip Review, Spring 2009\n\n==Art practice==\nRandy Lee Cutler works in various media from collage to performance, textual practices, digital e-books and posters. Her alias, Hedda Cabbage made an appearance at Fuse at the [[Vancouver Art Gallery]] co-presented by Live Biennale.\n\n===Saltwalks===\n\n''Saltwalks:Three Movements'' in conjunction with Access Gallery, was a work that consisted of performative \"interactions with the public initiated through taste tests of different kinds of edible salt\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Visualeyez|first1=Randy Lee Cutler|url=http://www.visualeyez.org/festival-2010/artists/randy-lee-cutler/|title=Ask me about salt}}</ref> As a work of social practice,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tse|first1=Naomi|title=Salt walks represent new form of social practice art|journal=The Source Forum of Diversity|date=May 27, 2014|volume=14|issue=9|url=http://thelasource.com/en/2014/05/26/salt-walks-represent-new-form-of-social-practice-art/}}</ref> the walks began with a salt tasting and led into an understanding salt's influence in social and cultural development.  The three walks were each navigated within a theme.  The first theme of herbal medicine featured Chinese herbal remedies with herbalist Albert Fok  The second on food preservation exposed participants to the influence salt and salt extraction had on food, the geography, and harvests and featured local artist Howie Tsui.  The final walk focused on the crystal structures of salt towards a vibrational healing energy power and featured a visit with local Chinatown crystal shop owner, Edward Gutierrez.\n\n===Open Wide===\n\nIn 2014 she released ''Open Wide: An Abecedarium for the Great Digestive System'', an [[ebook]] on digestion as a metaphor for experience.  The book mimics the digestive system, and its chronology is run by the alphabet.  It features illustrations, media and sound by [[Abbas Akhavan]], Myron Campbell, Gaye Chan, John Cussans, [[Geoffrey Farmer]], Kristina Fiedrich, Monique Fouquet, [[Allison Hrabluik]], Elvira Hufschmid, Ingrid Koenig, [[Germaine Koh]], [[Elizabeth MacKenzie]], [[Liz Magor]], Graham Meisner, Cindy Mochizuki, Damian Moppett, Ranu Mukherjee, Ryan Peter, [[Marina Roy]], Margit Schild, and [[Holly Schmidt]].\n\n===Select exhibitions/screenings===\n*''Salt Walks,'' for part of the group show Gleaners, Nanaimo Art Gallery, BC 2015\n*''A Joyful Wisdom'' collages and vitrine installation, part of the group show Beside Yourself, AHVA Gallery, Audain Art Centre, University of British Columbia, 2014\n*''Salt Walks: Three Movements,'' at VIVO Media Arts Centre, Vancouver, BC, 2014\n*''By Way of the Intersection,'' part of the Shelved curatorial project with Burnaby Art Gallery and Artspeak Gallery, Vancouver, BC, 2014\n*''Salt Walks: Three Movements,'' at Dr. Sun Yat-Sen Classical Chinese Garden in collaboration with Access Gallery, Vancouver, BC, 2014\n*''Kitchen Semiotics,'' Innovate Heritage: Conversations between Arts and Heritage, an international trans-disciplinary conference, Berlin, Germany, 2014\n\n==Interviews==\n*Jeremy Todd: A Conversation w/Randy Lee Cutler<ref>{{cite web|last1=VIVO Media Arts Centre|first1=Jeremy Todd|url=http://www.vivomediaarts.com/a-conversation-w-randy-lee-cutler/|title=A Conversation w/ Randy Lee Cutler}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cutler, Randy Lee}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:LGBT artists from Canada]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Art]]\n[[Category:Emily Carr University of Art and Design faculty]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Canada]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Selenite1", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added awards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randy_Lee_Cutler"}
{"title_page": "The Most Beautiful Girl in the World (1935 song)", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=September 2008}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name is Charlie O\u2019Brien-Schenk    = The Most Beautiful Girl in the World\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       =\n| artist     =\n| album      =\n| EP         =\n| written    =\n| published  = 1935\n| released   =\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Showtune]]\n| length     =\n| label      =\n| writer     =\n| composer   = [[Richard Rodgers]]\n| lyricist   = [[Lorenz Hart]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| title      =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| prev_track =\n| track_no   =\n| next_track =\n}}\n\"'''The Most Beautiful Girl In The World'''\" is a [[show tune]] from the [[1935 in music|1935]] [[Rodgers and Hart]] musical ''[[Jumbo (musical)|Jumbo]]''.\n\nA 1953 recording by [[Tommy Dorsey]] was a Billboard Top 40 hit per Joel Whitburn's ''Pop Memories 1890-1954''. Other recordings include those by [[Sonny Rollins]], [[Les Elgart|Les]] and [[Larry Elgart]], [[Vaughn Monroe]], [[Vic Damone]], [[Perry Como]], and [[Frank Sinatra]].\n\nIn the 1962 MGM movie, ''[[Billy Rose's Jumbo|Jumbo]]'',  the song was sung by renowned Los Angeles session singer, Jimmy Joyce, replacing the voice of actor Stephen Boyd\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Rodgers and Hart}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Most Beautiful Girl In The World, The}}\n[[Category:Songs with music by Richard Rodgers]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Lorenz Hart]]\n[[Category:1935 songs]]\n[[Category:1930s jazz standards]]\n[[Category:Songs from Rodgers and Hart musicals]]\n\n{{pop-standard-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=September 2008}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = The Most Beautiful Girl in the World\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       =\n| artist     =\n| album      =\n| EP         =\n| written    =\n| published  = 1935\n| released   =\n| format     =\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Showtune]]\n| length     =\n| label      =\n| writer     =\n| composer   = [[Richard Rodgers]]\n| lyricist   = [[Lorenz Hart]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| title      =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| prev_track =\n| track_no   =\n| next_track =\n}}\n\"'''The Most Beautiful Girl In The World'''\" is a [[show tune]] from the [[1935 in music|1935]] [[Rodgers and Hart]] musical ''[[Jumbo (musical)|Jumbo]]''.\n\nA 1953 recording by [[Tommy Dorsey]] was a Billboard Top 40 hit per Joel Whitburn's ''Pop Memories 1890-1954''. Other recordings include those by [[Sonny Rollins]], [[Les Elgart|Les]] and [[Larry Elgart]], [[Vaughn Monroe]], [[Vic Damone]], [[Perry Como]], and [[Frank Sinatra]].\n\nIn the 1962 MGM movie, ''[[Billy Rose's Jumbo|Jumbo]]'',  the song was sung by renowned Los Angeles session singer, Jimmy Joyce, replacing the voice of actor Stephen Boyd\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Rodgers and Hart}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Most Beautiful Girl In The World, The}}\n[[Category:Songs with music by Richard Rodgers]]\n[[Category:Songs with lyrics by Lorenz Hart]]\n[[Category:1935 songs]]\n[[Category:1930s jazz standards]]\n[[Category:Songs from Rodgers and Hart musicals]]\n\n{{pop-standard-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2600:100c:b25e:2548:b010:1b7a:e633:dc4f", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Most_Beautiful_Girl_in_the_World_(1935_song)"}
{"title_page": "Shannon McFerran", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian rules footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name                 = Shannon McFerran\n| image                = \n| alt                  = \n| caption              = \n| fullname             = \n| nickname             = \n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1979|06|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place          = \n| originalteam         = \n| height               = 168 cm\n| weight               = <!-- ## kg -->\n| position             = Rover\n| club1                = [[St Albans Spurs]]\n| sooyears1            = 1998 - 2011\n| sooteam1             = [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victoria]]\n| soogames_goals1      = \n| coachyears1       = 7\n| coachclub1           = St Albans Youth Girls<br>St Kilda Sharks<br>Collingwood AFLW (development coach)<br>Carlton VFLW head coach<br>Carlton AFLW Assistant coach\n| coachgames(wins)     = \n| statsend             = \n| pcupdate             = \n| repstatsend          = \n| coachstatsend        =\n| nationalyears1       = 2006\n| nationalteam1        = [[Australia women's international rules football team|Australia]]\n| nationalgames_goals1 =  \n| careerhighlights     = Premierships 2004, 2012, 2016 (Deer Park)\n}}\n\n'''Shannon McFerran''' (born 13 June 1979<ref name=\"footballbudget\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mediatonic.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2009/05/2009-rd-10.pdf | title=National Women's Football Championship | publisher=MediaTonic | work=Football Budget | date=30 May 2009 | accessdate=5 January 2012 | pages=22}}</ref>) is an [[Australian rules football]] player in the [[Victorian Women's Football League]]. She currently plays at St Kilda Sharks women's football team.\n\n==Playing career==\nMcFerran began playing for a St Albans FC boys' team at the age of nine. She played at St Albans with the boys until 12 years of age as girls could not play with boys after age 12. She went into umpiring and umpired in the FDFL now WRFL umpiring the boundary before taking up the field. At 17 McFerran joined the Sunshine YCW Spurs Women's football team. Sunshine moved to St Albans in 2000. She became captain of the Spurs in 2005. McFerran was part of the 2004 and 2011 premierships at St Albans Spurs.<ref name=\"vwfl\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=1-3068-0-0-0&sID=30737&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=15839556 | title=Shannon McFerran to play game 200 this Saturday | publisher=Victorian Women's Football League | date=27 May 2011 | accessdate=5 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007 Shannon was one of two Victorian Women's Football League representatives in the [[E. J. Whitten Legends Game|E. J. Whitten legends match]] where she played alongside former [[Australian Football League]] players such as [[Scott Cummings]], [[Nick Holland]], [[Mick Martyn (Australian footballer)|Mick Martyn]] and [[Nicky Winmar]].<ref name=\"aust-teacher\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=0-3068-0-0-0&sID=55665&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=5178386 | title=Up There Mcferran! State's Top Female AFL Player Takes a Speccy | work=Australian Teacher Magazine | date=March 2008 | accessdate=5 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009 she was diagnosed with an [[acoustic neuroma]], a tumour in the canal that connects the brain and ear. Despite losing hearing in her left ear, she played out the 2009 season. She was named All - Australian captain and was best on ground in the grand final at the Australian AFL championships, she also won the Debbie Lee medal for player of the championships.<ref name=\"vwfl\"/><ref name=\"heraldsun1\">{{cite news | url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/shannon-mcferran-played-last-season-of-football-with-a-brain-tumour/story-fn53kl6q-1225855674685 | title=Shannon McFerran played last season of football with a brain tumour | work=Herald Sun | date=20 April 2010 | accessdate=5 January 2012 | author=Critchley, Cheryl}}</ref>\n\nAfter surgery to remove the tumour in December 2009, she sat out the 2010 season. Returning after a season on the sidelines, McFerran played her 200th VWFL match for St Albans in May 2011.<ref name=\"vwfl\"/><ref name=\"age1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/top-woman-footballer-inspires-on-and-off-the-field-20110308-1bmlg.html | title=Top woman footballer inspires on and off the field | work=The Age | date=9 March 2011 | accessdate=5 January 2012 | author=Hanlon, Peter}}</ref><ref name=\"star1\">{{cite news | url=http://www.starnewsgroup.com.au/star/sunshne-ardeer-albion/286/story/129121.html | title=Back from brink- Back in the game | work=Albion Star |publisher=Star News Group| date=1 March 2011 | accessdate=5 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nShe has been named as best and fairest player (Helen Lambert medal) in the Victorian women's league five times and is a 10 time best and fairest club winner.<ref name=\"vwfl\"/>\n\nShe has represented Victoria 12 times, captained Victoria a number of times and was All Australian captain 2009 and 2011. She retired from playing at St Kilda Sharks and took on the role of head coach in 2015. In 2009, she featured in Women's Health magazine and was most recently named in the top 100 Sport women in Australia.\nMost recently Shannon was a development coach at Collingwood in the AFLW. She is now the head coach of Carltons VFLW team and assistant coach in Carltons AFLW team.\n\n==International rules football==\nMcFerran was a member of the [[Australia women's international rules football team]] that played against [[Ireland women's international rules football team|Ireland]] in the [[2006 Ladies' International Rules Series]]. <ref name=\"girlsplayfooty151116\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.is/20170316152023/http://girlsplayfooty.com/2016/11/reliving-the-one-and-only-womens-international-rules-series-10-years-on.html#selection-1217.1-1217.4|title=Reliving the one and only Women's International Rules series 10 years on|publisher=girlsplayfooty.com|date=15 November 2016|accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=worldfootynews141106>{{cite web|url=https://archive.is/20130616130039/http://www.worldfootynews.com/article.php/20061109110343227|title=Brave Aussie ladies like ewes to the slaughter in Ireland|publisher=www.worldfootynews.com|date=14 November 2006|accessdate=16 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"sportsfile041106\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsfile.com/more-images/D0611031/|title=Ireland v Australia \u2013 Ladies International Rules Series 2nd Test Photos|date=4 November 2006|publisher=www.sportsfile.com|accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McFerran, Shannon}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Victorian Women's Football League players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Australia women's international rules football team players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian rules footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name                 = Shannon McFerran\n| image                = \n| alt                  = \n| caption              = \n| fullname             = \n| nickname             = \n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1979|06|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place          = \n| originalteam         = \n| height               = 168 cm\n| weight               = <!-- ## kg -->\n| position             = Rover\n| club1                = [[St Albans Spurs]]\n| sooyears1            = 1998 - 2011\n| sooteam1             = [[Victoria Australian rules football team|Victoria]]\n| soogames_goals1      = \n| coachyears1       = 7\n| coachclub1           = St Albans Youth Girls<br>St Kilda Sharks<br>Collingwood AFLW (development coach)<br>Carlton VFLW head coach<br>Carlton AFLW Assistant coach\n| coachgames(wins)     = \n| statsend             = \n| pcupdate             = \n| repstatsend          = \n| coachstatsend        =\n| nationalyears1       = 2006\n| nationalteam1        = [[Australia women's international rules football team|Australia]]\n| nationalgames_goals1 =  \n| careerhighlights     = Premierships 2004, 2012, 2016 (Deer Park)\n}}\n\n'''Shannon McFerran''' (born 13 June 1979<ref name=\"footballbudget\">{{cite web | url=http://www.mediatonic.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2009/05/2009-rd-10.pdf | title=National Women's Football Championship | publisher=MediaTonic | work=Football Budget | date=30 May 2009 | accessdate=5 January 2012 | pages=22}}</ref>) is an [[Australian rules football]] player in the [[Victorian Women's Football League]]. She currently plays at St Kilda Sharks women's football team.\n\n==Playing career==\nMcFerran began playing for a St Albans FC boys' team at the age of nine. She played at St Albans with the boys until 12 years of age as girls could not play with boys after age 12. She went into umpiring and umpired in the FDFL now WRFL umpiring the boundary before taking up the field. At 17 McFerran joined the Sunshine YCW Spurs Women's football team. Sunshine moved to St Albans in 2000. She became captain of the Spurs in 2005. McFerran was part of the 2004 and 2011 premierships at St Albans Spurs.<ref name=\"vwfl\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=1-3068-0-0-0&sID=30737&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=15839556 | title=Shannon McFerran to play game 200 this Saturday | publisher=Victorian Women's Football League | date=27 May 2011 | accessdate=5 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2007 Shannon was one of two Victorian Women's Football League representatives in the [[E. J. Whitten Legends Game|E. J. Whitten legends match]] where she played alongside former [[Australian Football League]] players such as [[Scott Cummings]], [[Nick Holland]], [[Mick Martyn (Australian footballer)|Mick Martyn]] and [[Nicky Winmar]].<ref name=\"aust-teacher\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=0-3068-0-0-0&sID=55665&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=5178386 | title=Up There Mcferran! State's Top Female AFL Player Takes a Speccy | work=Australian Teacher Magazine | date=March 2008 | accessdate=5 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009 she was diagnosed with an [[acoustic neuroma]], a tumour in the canal that connects the brain and ear. Despite losing hearing in her left ear, she played out the 2009 season. She was named All - Australian captain and was best on ground in the grand final at the Australian AFL championships, she also won the Debbie Lee medal for player of the championships.<ref name=\"vwfl\"/><ref name=\"heraldsun1\">{{cite news | url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/shannon-mcferran-played-last-season-of-football-with-a-brain-tumour/story-fn53kl6q-1225855674685 | title=Shannon McFerran played last season of football with a brain tumour | work=Herald Sun | date=20 April 2010 | accessdate=5 January 2012 | author=Critchley, Cheryl}}</ref>\n\nAfter surgery to remove the tumour in December 2009, she sat out the 2010 season. Returning after a season on the sidelines, McFerran played her 200th VWFL match for St Albans in May 2011.<ref name=\"vwfl\"/><ref name=\"age1\">{{cite web | url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/top-woman-footballer-inspires-on-and-off-the-field-20110308-1bmlg.html | title=Top woman footballer inspires on and off the field | work=The Age | date=9 March 2011 | accessdate=5 January 2012 | author=Hanlon, Peter}}</ref><ref name=\"star1\">{{cite news | url=http://www.starnewsgroup.com.au/star/sunshne-ardeer-albion/286/story/129121.html | title=Back from brink- Back in the game | work=Albion Star |publisher=Star News Group| date=1 March 2011 | accessdate=5 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nShe has been named as best and fairest player (Helen Lambert medal) in the Victorian women's league five times and is a 10 time best and fairest club winner.<ref name=\"vwfl\"/>\n\nShe has represented Victoria 12 times, captained Victoria a number of times and was All Australian captain 2009 and 2011. She retired from playing at St Kilda Sharks and took on the role of head coach in 2015. In 2009, she featured in Women's Health magazine and was most recently named in the top 100 Sport women in Australia.\nMost recently Shannon was a development coach at Collingwood in the AFLW. She is now the head coach of Carltons VFLW team and assistant coach in Carltons AFLW team.\n\n==International rules football==\nMcFerran was a member of the [[Australia women's international rules football team]] that played against [[Ireland women's international rules football team|Ireland]] in the [[2006 Ladies International Rules Series]]. <ref name=\"girlsplayfooty151116\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.is/20170316152023/http://girlsplayfooty.com/2016/11/reliving-the-one-and-only-womens-international-rules-series-10-years-on.html#selection-1217.1-1217.4|title=Reliving the one and only Women's International Rules series 10 years on|publisher=girlsplayfooty.com|date=15 November 2016|accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=worldfootynews141106>{{cite web|url=https://archive.is/20130616130039/http://www.worldfootynews.com/article.php/20061109110343227|title=Brave Aussie ladies like ewes to the slaughter in Ireland|publisher=www.worldfootynews.com|date=14 November 2006|accessdate=16 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"sportsfile041106\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsfile.com/more-images/D0611031/|title=Ireland v Australia \u2013 Ladies International Rules Series 2nd Test Photos|date=4 November 2006|publisher=www.sportsfile.com|accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McFerran, Shannon}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Victorian Women's Football League players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Australia women's international rules football team players]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInternational rules football:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_McFerran"}
